on of territorial claims and noble status. These works reveal that the qualities traditionally used to define sovereignty-lineage and gender among them-are in fact mobile and contingent. In medieval literary texts, as McCracken demonstrates, human dominion over animals is a disputed model for sovereign relations among people: it justifies exploitation even as it mandates protection and care, and it depends on reiterations of human-animal difference that paradoxically expose the tenuous nature of human exceptionalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAnimalsxSymbolic aspectszFrancexHistory. 0aFrench literatureyTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 0aHides and skins in literature. 0aHides and skinsxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistory. 0aHides and skinsxSymbolic aspectszFrancexHistory. 0aHuman-animal relationships in literature. 0aHuman-animal relationshipsxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistory. 0aSovereignty in literature. 4aFrance. 4aanimality. 4adomestication. 4adominion. 4agender. 4amedieval literature. 4aprotection. 4asovereignty. 70(DE-601)1045354740(DE-588)4129108-6aMittelalter2gnd 70(DE-601)1048052180(DE-588)4184194-3aSymbolik2gnd 70(DE-601)1061409140(DE-588)4060087-7aTiere2gnd 70(DE-601)1062312860(DE-588)4038639-9aMensch2gnd 70(DE-601)1062450150(DE-588)4035964-5aLiteratur2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226459080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226459080.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles